## Diagnosis

The active label is rendering on the **wrong side** of its anchor point because the positioning math assumes the label grows leftward from a right-edge anchor, but the element it's anchored to has its own `left`/`transform` origin pointing rightward into the viewport.

Let me trace the exact failure chain:

### Root Cause

**AP-072 — Conflicting coordinate-space origins between sibling and absolute-positioned elements.**

The hover labels are positioned in a **right-aligned gutter** using something like:

```css
right: 100%;          /* grow leftward from the rail */
transform-origin: right center;
```

The active label is almost certainly being anchored to the **tick mark itself** (a small element whose `left` position is already offset inward from the rail edge), and then using `left: 100%` or `translateX(+N)` — which pushes it **further right** instead of mirroring the hover label's **leftward** expansion.

Switching the anchor from the inner tick to the notch container didn't help because the notch container likely still has a `left: 50%` or `translateX(-50%)` centering transform active, so its coordinate origin is the center of the rail, not the left edge of the gutter.

The precise anti-pattern: **the active label shares no common positioning parent with the hover labels**, so their `right: 100%` values resolve against different containing blocks and produce different physical positions.

---

## Investigation — What the Code Looks Like Now

```
ScrollSpy
├── .rail  (position: relative, fixed to right viewport edge)
│   ├── .tick  (position: absolute, left: 50%, transform: translateX(-50%))
│   │   └── .notch  (position: absolute)
│   │       └── .active-label  ← anchored here, but wrong side
│   └── .hover-label  (position: absolute, right: 100%)  ← correct side
```

The hover labels live as **direct children of `.rail`** and use `right: 100%` against the rail's width.  
The active label lives inside `.notch` (or `.tick`), so `right: 100%` resolves against the notch/tick width, which is tiny — producing a completely different physical X position.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Move the active label to be a sibling of the hover labels

Both label types must share the **same positioning parent** (`.rail`) so that `right: 100%` resolves identically for both.

**`components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.tsx`** (or `.jsx`):

```tsx
// BEFORE — active label rendered inside the tick/notch subtree
<li key={section.id} className="relative">
  <span className="tick" style={{ top: offset }}>
    <span className="notch">
      {isActive && (
        <span className="label label--active">{section.label}</span>  // ❌ wrong parent
      )}
    </span>
  </span>
  <span className="label label--hover">{section.label}</span>
</li>

// AFTER — active label is a sibling of the hover label, same containing block
<li key={section.id} className="relative">
  <span className="tick" style={{ top: offset }}>
    <span className="notch" />
  </span>

  {/* Both labels share the same containing block: the <li> or .rail */}
  <span
    className={`label label--hover ${isActive ? 'label--active' : ''}`}
    aria-current={isActive ? 'true' : undefined}
  >
    {section.label}
  </span>
</li>
```

> If you need the active label to be visually distinct (different size/weight/color) without duplicating markup, just toggle a modifier class on the **single** label element. One element, two visual states.

### Step 2 — Unify label positioning in CSS/Tailwind

**`components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.css`** (or the Tailwind layer):

```css
/* ─── ScrollSpy Rail ─────────────────────────────── */
.scroll-spy-rail {
  position: fixed;
  right: 0;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: flex-end;   /* rail hugs right edge */
  gap: var(--spy-gap, 1.5rem);
  z-index: 50;
  /* No width — the labels extend leftward, not rightward */
}

/* ─── Tick + Notch ───────────────────────────────── */
.scroll-spy-tick {
  position: relative;
  width: var(--tick-w, 8px);
  height: var(--tick-w, 8px);
  border-radius: 50%;
  background: currentColor;
  /* ⚠️  NO left/translateX here — keep it right-aligned */
  margin-right: var(--rail-pad, 12px);
}

/* ─── Label — shared base ────────────────────────── */
.scroll-spy-label {
  position: absolute;
  right: calc(100% + var(--rail-pad, 12px)); /* ← LEFT of the rail */
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  white-space: nowrap;
  text-align: right;               /* text reads right-to-left from rail */

  /* hidden by default */
  opacity: 0;
  pointer-events: none;
  transition: opacity 150ms ease, font-weight 150ms ease;
}

/* ─── Hover state ────────────────────────────────── */
.scroll-spy-item:hover .scroll-spy-label {
  opacity: 1;
  pointer-events: auto;
}

/* ─── Active state — joins the SAME stack, just always visible ── */
.scroll-spy-label--active {
  opacity: 1;                      /* always shown   */
  pointer-events: auto;
  font-weight: 600;                /* visually distinct */
  color: var(--color-accent);
  /* NO different right/left/transform — it sits in exactly the same gutter */
}
```

### Step 3 — If using Tailwind classes inline

```tsx
// components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.tsx
const labelBase = [
  'absolute',
  'right-full',          // ← same as right: 100% — grows LEFT
  '-translate-y-1/2',
  'top-1/2',
  'whitespace-nowrap',
  'text-right',
  'pr-3',                // gap between label and rail
  'opacity-0',
  'pointer-events-none',
  'transition-opacity',
].join(' ');

const labelActive = 'opacity-100 pointer-events-auto font-semibold text-accent-500';
const labelHover  = 'group-hover:opacity-100 group-hover:pointer-events-auto';

// In JSX — single element, toggled classes:
<span
  className={`${labelBase} ${isActive ? labelActive : labelHover}`}
>
  {section.label}
</span>
```

Add `group` to the `<li>` for the hover selector to work:

```tsx
<li key={section.id} className="relative group flex items-center justify-end">
  <span className="scroll-spy-tick" />
  <span className={`${labelBase} ${isActive ? labelActive : labelHover}`}>
    {section.label}
  </span>
</li>
```

---

## Why Your Previous Fix Didn't Work

Changing the anchor from the **tick** to the **notch** moved the containing block by only a few pixels (the notch is inside the tick, both are tiny). The real containing block mismatch — active label inside the tick subtree vs. hover label as a rail sibling — remained completely intact. You shuffled chairs inside the wrong room.

---

## Principle

**P-1 — Same visual stack → same positioning parent.**  
Any set of elements that must align to a common gutter must share an identical containing block. Mixing `position: absolute` ancestry depths for elements that are supposed to overlap/align is the primary source of "it's in the right place in DOM inspector but wrong on screen" bugs. Resolve this structurally (same parent) before touching `right`/`left` values — coordinate-space arithmetic cannot fix a broken containing-block hierarchy.
